Self-Assembling Orbital Solar Swarms (SAOSS)

A Complete Architecture for Safe, Scalable Space-Based Solar Power

Author: Ouadi Maakoul + chatGpt+ Gemini+ Deepseek+ Claude 

---

EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

Self-Assembling Orbital Solar Swarms (SAOSS) presents a distributed, autonomous architecture for space-based solar power that leverages Starship-scale launch capacity to achieve grid-competitive energy at $0.07/kWh. The system replaces monolithic megastructures with millions of cooperative 13-kg Solar Swarm Units (SSUs) that self-organize in LEO, forming a kilometer-scale sparse phased array for safe microwave power transmission.

Key Innovations:

1. Meta-Safety Architecture - Hardware-enforced power density limits prevent weaponization
2. Swarm Autonomy - Distributed control eliminates single-point failures
3. Incremental Scalability - Deployable from 10 kW to 1 GW via reusable launch vehicles
4. Economic Viability - Capital costs of $3B for 660 MW deliverable power

This document provides complete mathematical foundations, simulation code, and hardware specifications for peer review and implementation.

