1. INTRODUCTION & MOTIVATION

1.1 The Energy Trilemma

Global energy demand will increase 50% by 2050 while terrestrial renewables face fundamental limits:

· Solar PV: ~20% capacity factor, storage requirements
· Wind: ~35% capacity factor, geographical constraints
· Nuclear: High capital costs, political barriers
· Fossil Fuels: CO₂ emissions, finite resources

Space-based solar power (SBSP) offers continuous availability (99% capacity factor) at 5-10× higher energy density than terrestrial alternatives, but historical proposals have been economically prohibitive due to:

1. Massive upfront capital requirements ($1T+)
2. Launch cost barriers ($10,000+/kg historically)
3. Weaponization concerns
4. Single-point failure risks

1.2 The SAOSHypothesis

Core Assertion: A distributed swarm architecture, enabled by Starship-scale launch economics and advances in swarm robotics, can overcome the historical barriers to SBSP by:

1. Reducing capital risk through incremental deployment
2. Enforcing intrinsic safety via physical/geometric constraints
3. Enabling political acceptance through distributed control and open protocols

1.3 Research Questions

This work addresses:

1. How can SBSP systems be designed to scale incrementally without catastrophic failure modes?
2. What architectural constraints ensure non-weaponizability under adversarial control?
3. How can orbital energy infrastructure align with existing launch and regulatory frameworks?
4. What swarm control algorithms enable kilometer-scale phase coherence for power transmission?

