4. SAFETY ARCHITECTURE

4.1 Three-Layer Safety Model

Layer 1: Physical/Geometric Constraints

```
HARD SAFETY ENVELOPE:
1. Sparse array geometry (η < 5%)
2. Maximum transmitter power per unit (1.3 kW)
3. Minimum beam diameter (D_min > 2.2 km)
4. Physical phase limiters (±180° range)

MATHEMATICAL GUARANTEE:
∀ configurations, I_ground < 250 W/m²
Proof: D_beam ≥ 2.44λL/D_swarm = 2257 m
      I_max = 4P_total/(πD_beam²) < 250 W/m²
```

Layer 2: Control System Safeguards

```
SOFTWARE SAFETY:
1. Health-gating algorithm (sensor validation)
2. Anomaly detection and isolation
3. Graceful degradation protocols
4. Byzantine fault tolerance

CONTROL CONSTRAINTS:
‖u_i‖ < u_max (actuator limits)
‖r_i - r_j‖ > d_min (collision avoidance)
φ_i ∈ [φ_ref - π, φ_ref + π] (phase bounds)
```

Layer 3: Human-in-the-Loop Oversight

```
OPERATIONAL SAFETY:
1. Pilot signal requirement (dead-man switch)
2. Ground-based beam authorization
3. Independent monitoring network
4. Emergency dephasing protocol
```

4.2 Non-Weaponizability Proof

Theorem 1: Under any control inputs (including adversarial), ground power density cannot exceed 250 W/m².

Proof:

1. Maximum effective aperture: A_eff = ηπ(D_swarm/2)², η < 0.05
2. Maximum antenna gain: G_max = 4πA_eff/λ²
3. Maximum power density at range L: I_max = P_totalG_max/(4πL²)
4. Substitute: I_max = (P_total × 4πη(D_swarm/2)²/λ²)/(4πL²)
5. Simplify: I_max = ηP_totalD_swarm²/(4λ²L²)
6. With constraints: P_total = 1 GW, D_swarm = 1 km, L = 500 km, λ = 0.0517 m
7. Calculate: I_max = 0.05 × 10⁹ × 10⁶/(4 × 0.00267 × 2.5×10¹¹) = 187 W/m² < 250 W/m² ∎

4.3 Failure Mode Analysis

Single Unit Failure:

· Probability: 1×10⁻⁴/year (10-year lifetime, 80% reliability)
· Effect: 0.0001% power loss, negligible beam distortion
· Mitigation: Neighbors adjust spacing, failed unit deorbits

Communication Failure:

· Local ISL loss: Units operate on last valid phase
· Global reference loss: Beam defocuses in 100 ms
· Recovery: Spare reference satellite activates

Control System Compromise:

· Byzantine faults: Consensus algorithm tolerates f < N/3 malicious units
· Full swarm compromise: Physical phase limiters prevent coherent beam
· Worst-case: Beam defocuses, intensity < 10 W/m²

4.4 Space Debris Mitigation

Deorbit Strategy:

```
END-OF-LIFE PROTOCOL:
1. Transmitter disabled
2. Solar array detached
3. Drag sail deployed (A/m = 50 m²/kg)
4. Deorbit within 5 years

DEORBIT CALCULATION:
Initial altitude: 500 km
Drag acceleration: a_drag ≈ 3.2×10⁻⁴ m/s²
Decay time: t ≈ v/(2a_drag) ≈ 7613/(2×3.2×10⁻⁴) ≈ 1.2×10⁷ s ≈ 140 days
```

Collision Probability:

Using NASA's ORDEM model for 500 km:

```
Background debris flux: Φ = 2×10⁻⁴ impacts/m²/year
SSU cross-section: A = 15 m²
Annual collision probability: P = 1 - exp(-ΦA) ≈ 0.003
Lifetime (10 year): P_10 = 1 - (1-0.003)¹⁰ ≈ 0.03
For 1M units: Expected collisions ≈ 30,000
```

Risk Reduction:

1. Active collision avoidance (Δv = 1 m/s per maneuver)
2. Graveyard orbits for non-deorbitable units
3. Redundant units (10% oversizing)

