9.4 Risk Management Framework

9.4.1 Risk Assessment Matrix

```
SEVERITY              PROBABILITY
              Rare    Unlikely   Possible   Likely   Certain
Catastrophic  Monitor  Mitigate  Mitigate  Avoid    Avoid
Critical      Accept   Monitor   Mitigate  Mitigate Avoid
Moderate      Accept   Accept    Monitor   Mitigate Mitigate
Minor         Accept   Accept    Accept    Monitor  Monitor
Insignificant Accept   Accept    Accept    Accept   Accept
```

9.4.2 Contingency Plans

```
CONTINGENCY 1: Partial System Failure
Plan: Operate at reduced capacity, prioritize critical loads
Resources: Spare units, redundant systems
Activation: Automatic degradation

CONTINGENCY 2: Complete System Failure
Plan: Safe deorbiting, insurance claim
Resources: Deorbit propulsion, emergency fund
Activation: Manual command

CONTINGENCY 3: Political Opposition
Plan: Relocate to friendly jurisdiction
Resources: International partnerships, legal team
Activation: Gradual escalation
```

---

10. CONCLUSION & FUTURE WORK

10.1 Summary of Contributions

This dissertation has demonstrated that Self-Assembling Orbital Solar Swarms represent a viable pathway to space-based solar power through:

1. Distributed Architecture: Replacing monolithic structures with autonomous swarms eliminates single-point failures and enables incremental deployment.
2. Meta-Safety Design: Hardware-enforced power density limits ensure non-weaponizability under any control scenario.
3. Economic Viability: Leveraging Starship-scale launch economics achieves LCOE of $0.07/kWh at scale.
4. Technical Feasibility: Detailed simulations show that kilometer-scale phase coherence is achievable with existing technology.
5. Political Acceptability: The Open Energy Protocol and international oversight framework address security concerns.

